summary: Real progress in the fight against TB requires that we think of people with TB as people. Such thinking leads to focus on law...
text: Real progress in the fight against TB requires that we think of people with TB as people. Such thinking leads to focus on law and policy reform to create health systems that foster trust and dignity rather than fear. This is why only human rights can chart a successful response to TB.
source:
John Stephens at Africa is a Country. Why we’re losing the fight against TB

O’Neill Institute for National and Global Health Law

body:
What is an irregular period?

I’ve still been on schedule within a day or so, but duration and flow has been varying noticeably from month to month. How much inconsistency is cause for concern, if it’s cause for concern at all when cycle length is still roughly the same?

I’m an overweight 31 year old cis woman, but no major health issues that I’m aware of other than being fat and out of shape. I get cramps but not debilitating ones (just painful enough to be annoying), and they usually go away after a single dose of Aleve.
